<strong>The lecture notes are a collaborative effort of the participants in the course. You are not required to contribute to the lecture notes, but are encouraged to do so. Together, we can create resources that will be helpful to everyone.</strong></p>
<h2> <span class="mw-headline" id="Notes_for_Week_2:_3.2._The_Supply_Equation.2C_Schedule.2C_and_Curve">Notes for Week 2: 3.2. The Supply Equation, Schedule, and Curve</span></h2>
<p>The formula of the Supply is $$[Q&#95;{x&#95;s}=f(P&#95;x, Price&#95;{Inputs}, Technology)]$$.</p>
<p><br />$$Q&#95;{x&#95;s}$$=quantity of supply
<br />$$P&#95;x$$=price of tomatoes
<br />$$Price&#95;{Inputs}$$=costs of creating supply
<br />Technology=technology</p>
<p>To create the table will be easy to imagine as a farmer(supplier) of tomato. If the price will be up then we the farmer will be able to sell much more of tomato; the quantity of supply will increase in proportion.</p>
<p>In that way, the Supply Curve will be the right-up-line in the Px/Qx diagram.
The line shows that if the Px will be up(/down), then Qx will be up(/down) which tells the change of the price would turn into the change in the quantity of supply.</p>
<p>(simon yuan) Be alerted that the quiz question: the price of Apple/Banana changes, the demand/demand curve for wine change or not.... is really confusing...just try again to get the Banana...Banana or wine...wine...</p>
<p></p>

